Analysis of COVID-19 Serial Interval

Chris Panlasigui

1 Introduction

This is a study of the incubation time of COVID-19 infections based on 468 events of transmission in China: https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/eid/article/26/6/20-0357_article. The main research questions are:

  1. Are there pre-symptomatic transmissions?
  2. What is the mean incubation time?
  3. Does the incubation time differ for same-city transmission?
  4. Is the incubation time shorter for same-household transmission?

2 Materials

The following softwares and packages will be used in the retrieval, parsing and analysis:

  • R version 3.6.1 (2019-07-05)
  • RStudio Version 1.2.1335
  • R packages:
    • tidyverse: data manipulation
    • kableExtra: table display
    • broom: tidying R output into dataframes
    • bookdown for general display of figure, table and references
  • Online report
    • https://github.com/MeyersLabUTexas/COVID-19
library(tidyverse)
library(readxl)
library(kableExtra)
library(bookdown)
library(broom)

3 Methods

3.1 Data Parsing

Data include only confirmed cases compiled online from 18 provincial centers for disease control and prevention.

download.file("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/MeyersLabUTexas/COVID-19/master/Table%20S5.xlsx", "rawData.xlsx")
covid19 <- read_excel("rawData.xlsx", skip=1, col_names = TRUE)

4.2 Data visualization

4.2.1 Distribution of serial intervals

names(covid19)
 [1] "Event index"                    "Index ID"                      
 [3] "Secondary ID"                   "City"                          
 [5] "Province"                       "Index - infection location"    
 [7] "Index - symptom onset date"     "Index - Age"                   
 [9] "Index - Sex"                    "Secondary - infection location"
[11] "Seconday - symptom onset date"  "Seconday - Age"                
[13] "Seconday-Sex"                   "Contact type"                  
[15] "URL"                            "Data source"                   
names(covid19) <- c("event_index", "index_id", "secondary_id", "city",
              "province", "index_infect_location", "index_symptom_onset_date",
              "index_age", "index_sex", "secondary_infect_location", 
              "secondary_symptom_onset_date", "secondary_age", "secondary_sex", 
              "contact_type", "url", "data_source")
covid19 <- covid19 %>% mutate(serial_int = secondary_symptom_onset_date - index_symptom_onset_date)
covid19 %>% ggplot(aes(x = serial_int))+
  geom_histogram(bins = 30, color = 'grey30', fill = 'white') +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0, color = 'red', linetype = 'dashed') +
  theme_bw() + labs(title = 'Estimated serial interval distribution for COVID-19', x = 'Serial interval, d', y = 'Frequency')

Figure 4.1: estimated serial interval time for COVID-19 from 468 transmission events between January 21 - February 28, 2020 in mainland China

The frequency for all reported infection events, n=468, across 93 cities. COVID-19 transmission from asymptomatic or mildly symptomatic case-patience are indicated by the negative serial intervals found on the left of the red vertical dashed lines.

covid19 %>% ggplot() + 
  geom_histogram(aes(x = serial_int, y=..density..), bins = 30, color = 'grey30', fill = 'white') + 
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0, color = 'red', linetype = 'dashed') + 
  stat_function(fun=dnorm, args = list(mean=mean(covid19$serial_int), 
                                       sd=sd(covid19$serial_int)), color='blue') +
  theme_bw() + labs(title = 'Density w/ fitted normal distributions', x = 'Serial interval, d')

Figure 4.2: estimated serial interval time with fitted normal distribution for COVID-19 from 468 transmission events between January 21 - February 28, 2020 in mainland China

The calculated density with fitted normal distribution in figure 4.1. COVID-19 transmission from asymptomatic or mildly symptomatic case-patience are indicated by the negative serial intervals found on the left of the red vertical dashed lines.

covid19Subset <- covid19 %>% filter(index_infect_location == secondary_infect_location)  

covid19Subset %>% ggplot(aes(x = serial_int)) + 
  geom_histogram(bins = 30, color = 'grey30', fill = 'white') +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0, color = 'red', linetype = 'dashed') +
  theme_bw() + labs(title = 'Intra-city serial interval distribution for COVID-19', 
                    x = 'Serial interval, d', y = 'Frequency')

Figure 4.3: estimated serial interval time for COVID-19 from a subset of transmission events between January 21 - February 28, 2020 in mainland China

The subset, n = 131, of infection in which the infector and infectee were infected in the reporting city. COVID-19 transmission from asymptomatic or mildly symptomatic case-patience are indicated by the negative serial intervals found on the left of the red vertical dashed lines.

covid19Subset %>% ggplot() + 
  geom_histogram(aes(x = serial_int, y =..density..), bins = 29, color = 'grey30', fill = 'white') +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0, color = 'red', linetype = 'dashed') +
  stat_function(fun=dnorm, args = list(mean=mean(covid19Subset$serial_int), 
                                       sd=sd(covid19Subset$serial_int)), color='blue') +
  theme_bw() + labs(title = 'Density w/ fitted normal distribution', 
                    x = 'Serial interval, d')

Figure 4.4: Estimated serial interval time for COVID-19 from a subset of transmission events between January 21 - February 28, 2020 in mainland China

The calculated density with fitted normal distribution in figure 4.3. COVID-19 transmission from asymptomatic or mildly symptomatic case-patience are indicated by the negative serial intervals found on the left of the red vertical dashed lines.

The estimated mean serial interval for all 468 transmission events is 3.96 days with 95% confidence interval of 3.52 to 4.4 days.

The Contact type column or variable in original data is a chr data type. To check how many levels of contact type, the data type is set to factor accordingly. The fct_count() can help in validation protocol.

covid19 <- covid19 %>% mutate_at(vars(contact_type), factor)
covid19$contact_type %>% fct_count() %>% kable(booktabs = TRUE, caption = 'Table of infection events by contact type') %>%

5 Statistical Analysis

5.1 Difference by contact type

The boxplot in Test whether the mean of the serial interval in a household transmission is significanlty different from the mean of the serial interval in a non-household transmission.

\[H_0: \overline{x}_{household} = \overline{x} _{nonhousehold}~\] \[H_a: \overline{x}_{household} \neq \overline{x} _{nonhousehold}~\]

covidContact <- covid19 %>% 
  select(serial_int, contact_type) %>%
  filter(contact_type %in% c('Household', 'Non-household'))
contactTtest <- t.test(serial_int ~ contact_type, data = covidContact)
tidy(contactTtest) %>% kable(booktabs = TRUE, caption = 'Table.') %>% 
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover"))
